mpire. Examining translations of Indian texts from the eighteenth century to the present, Niranjana urges post-colonial peoples to reconceive translation as a site for resistance and transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeconstruction. 0aHistoricism. 0aImperialism. 0aStructuralism (Literary analysis). 0aTranslating and interpreting. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aallegory.  aappropriation.  abenjamin.  acolonial india.  acolonialism.  acontrol.  aculture.  aderrida.  adisruption.  aempire.  aethnography.  aexotic other.  ageography.  ahistoricism.  ahistory of translation.  ahistory.  aimperialism.  ainequality.  ajacques derrida.  alanguage.  aliterary theory.  apaul de man.  apoetics.  apolitical actions.  apoliticized.  apolitics.  apost structuralism.  apostcolonialism.  apower structures.  aresistance.  atransformation.  atranslation studies.  atranslation.  atranslator.  aunequal power relations.  awalter benjamin.  awestern philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007451440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520911369?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911369423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520911369/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles